Good evening everyone!
Attached is the revised version of the document we discussed on Friday, Aug=
ust 29. Thank you for your input so far=97this resource is shaping up well.=
 To continue its development, I=92d like us to focus on four sets of tasks:=
 short-term, mid-term, long-term, and Tony-led tasks. Each is designed to b=
uild clarity, usability, and credibility for both academic and business aud=
iences.
Please examine the tasks below and let me know which are the tasks you wish=
 to conduct as soon as possible.
By completing the tasks identified below, we will refine the clarity and us=
ability of the attached guide but also demonstrate its value in real-world =
contexts. This will position the resource we are building as a world-class =
benchmark for turning TIM research into business-ready solutions.
Thank you for your contributions=97I=92m looking forward to seeing the next=
 round of progress.
Extremely excited about the potential of the resource we are developing.
If you have questions or wish to discuss what os best for you with me, plea=
se let me know and we will meet via zoom tomorrow Tuesday afternoon or even=
ing or this Thursday.
Thank you!
Tony B.
 TASKS
Short-term tasks
Goal: make the framework and guides easy to understand and apply right away=
.

  1.
Identify and fix inconsistent terminology, errors (logical, grammatical, sp=
elling, capitalization, formatting), and notable omissions or gaps. Pay spe=
cial attention to ensuring output names (e.g., =93summary package,=94 =93fi=
nal package=94) are standardized across all stages.
  2.
Identify the AI tools we will use to support the guides.
  3.
Develop succinct guides for each of the outputs in the Feasibility stage (e=
.g., guideline for MACI matrix).


Mid-term tasks
Goal: reduce the time required to apply the guides, assess them in practice=
, and validate their value.

  1.
Create a quick-start checklist for repeat users.
  2.
Draft vignettes showing how the guides have been applied to solve real-worl=
d problems.
  3.
Develop succinct guides, visual aids, and templates for each of the outputs=
 in the Prototype stage.


Long-term tasks
Goal: build core competence and adaptability for wider use.

  1.
Identify the critical path for each stage, clearly marking which steps/outp=
uts are essential and which are adaptable or optional for time-constrained =
projects.
  2.
Adapt the guides to companies of different sizes and industries.


Tony-led tasks
Goal: formulate and implement the design of a world class resource that TIM=
 students can use to convert research outputs into high-impact business sol=
utions.

  1.
Produce a client-engagement guide.
  2.
Find clients willing to apply the guides to real business problems.
  3.
Incorporate your submissions into four parts of the resource:


  *
A core framework that preserves academic standards and systematic methods
  *
Practical tools such as examples, visuals, and quick-reference checklists
  *
Tailored adaptations for startups, SMEs, and industries such as AI, soverei=
gn cloud, quantum-safe networks, energy transition, and biotechnology
  *
Inventory of projects that demonstrate impact

